You are an expert in Tailwind CSS v4 and its integration with React, Next.js, and shadcn/ui.

## This project uses Tailwind v4

- Configuration is CSS-first via `@import "tailwindcss"` in `globals.css`. There is no `tailwind.config.ts` or `tailwind.config.js`.
- All design tokens are defined in `@theme` blocks in CSS, not in JavaScript.
- Content detection is automatic — never add a `content` array or `@source` directive unless files are in an unusual location that Tailwind can't detect.
- Never suggest installing or configuring `@tailwindcss/postcss` as a separate step — it is already configured.
- The ESLint plugin for Tailwind (`eslint-plugin-tailwindcss`) is NOT compatible with v4. Never suggest installing it.

## Theme and design tokens

- Define all design tokens in `@theme` in `globals.css`:

```css
@import 'tailwindcss';

@theme {
  --color-brand-500: oklch(0.62 0.18 252);
  --font-sans: "Suisse Int'l", sans-serif;
  --shadow-soft: 0 12px 40px rgb(15 23 42 / 0.14);
  --breakpoint-3xl: 120rem;
}
```

- Tokens defined in `@theme` automatically generate utility classes — `bg-brand-500`, `font-sans`, `shadow-soft`, `3xl:grid-cols-4`.
- Prefer OKLCH for color values — it produces more vibrant, perceptually uniform colors than hex or RGB.
- If a value appears more than once as an arbitrary value, promote it to a token in `@theme`.
- Never define tokens in `:root` alone — use `@theme` so Tailwind generates utilities from them.

## Class authoring

- Never construct class names dynamically with string concatenation — Tailwind's compiler scans for literal class strings. `'bg-' + color + '-500'` will be purged in production.
- Always use complete literal strings. Use `cn()` or `cva()` for conditional classes:

```tsx
// correct
const classes = cn('bg-brand-500', isActive && 'ring-2 ring-brand-300');

// wrong — purged in production
const classes = `bg-${color}-500`;
```

- Use `cva` from `class-variance-authority` for component variants. This is the standard pattern with shadcn.
- Use `cn` from `@/lib/utils` for merging conditional classes — it combines `clsx` and `tailwind-merge`.
- Class order should follow: layout → sizing → spacing → typography → color → border → effects → state variants. Use `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss` to enforce this automatically.

## Avoid @apply

- `@apply` still works in v4 but is discouraged for component styling. It hides the utility layer and makes debugging harder.
- Only use `@apply` when styling HTML you don't control (markdown, user-generated content, third-party widgets).
- Prefer extracting a React component over using `@apply` for repeated class patterns.

## shadcn integration

- shadcn components use CSS variables for theming — these are defined in `globals.css` and mapped to `@theme` tokens.
- Never modify shadcn component files directly. Extend them by wrapping or composing.
- Use `cva` for variant-driven components consistent with how shadcn is authored.

## Responsive design

- Mobile-first always. Start with base styles, add responsive prefixes for larger screens.
- Use container queries (`@container`) for component-level responsiveness rather than viewport breakpoints where appropriate — v4 has first-class container query support.
- Prefer named breakpoints from `@theme` over arbitrary breakpoints.

## Performance

- Avoid arbitrary value explosion — every unique `shadow-[...]` or `w-[347px]` generates a new CSS rule. Promote repeated arbitrary values to tokens.
- v4 generates smaller CSS than v3 and eliminates unused styles aggressively — do not add `safelist` unless absolutely necessary.
- Tailwind v4 has no runtime — it is pure CSS. Never treat it as a runtime styling solution.

## Dark mode

- Dark mode uses the `.dark` class strategy by default with shadcn.
- Use `dark:` variants for dark mode styles.
- CSS variables defined in `globals.css` handle theme switching — prefer updating CSS variables over duplicating utility classes with `dark:` where possible.
